Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 64th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
This was a tough week to be optimistic. Last Saturday, Hamas terrorists bru=
tally murdered, raped, and kidnapped over a thousand Israeli civilians, inc=
luding kids and babies. The week since has been a parade of gut-wrenching i=
mage after gut-wrenching image. It=E2=80=99s impossible to imagine the pain=
 families are going through, and impossible to believe that this is million=
s=E2=80=99 of humans=E2=80=99 lived reality right now.=20
Our hearts go out to the people of Israel, Jews across the world, and the i=
nnocent people throughout the region, including Palestinians, who will suff=
er as a result of these acts of terror.=20
This week=E2=80=99s tragedies are a reminder that there is evil in the worl=
d. But there=E2=80=99s more goodness, as exemplified by the stories [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/51ad26de-9c9a-4d46-8366-4fc0fa9a1615?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of heroism [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/6882c4b8-5b7b-4d8a-8d27-c23690b1bb2d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/41d395bf-d28d-4d0d-b4af-96e4eff35f24?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] keep [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/d303188c-9ca3-4a58-97da-b88b00f19eee?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] emerging [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/a49f0d6f-c358-4300-806f-fea9e07c7dae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Every week, we try to share a little human goodness, and we=E2=80=99ll do t=
he same this week.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) Introducing Age of Miracles [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a24ffe9-53=
78-4e5d-9cb8-4000b34e9413?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. I=E2=80=99ve been cooking something up over the past few months=
 with the team at Turpentine [ https://substack.com/redirect/651938f4-0b8e-=
4899-a456-0be99e5b9bac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and I=E2=80=99m excited to finally get to share a little =
sneak peek with you.
Age of Miracles [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a24ffe9-5378-4e5d-9cb8-400=
0b34e9413?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] is a podcast about the industries helping to create a world of superabu=
ndance. Each season, over the course of ten jam-packed episodes, we=E2=80=
=99re going to go deep on one industry by talking to founders, investors, r=
esearchers, policy experts, and even skeptics to understand the challenges =
and opportunities at play.=20
Then we=E2=80=99re going to weave all of the conversations into a narrative=
 that we hope can serve as the best way to get up to speed on that industry=
 =E2=80=94 its history, dynamics, a snapshot of the current state, and some=
 dreaming about what happens if things go right.=20
The title Age of Miracles is a little tongue-in-cheek. I strongly believe t=
hat we can live in an Age of Miracles, but I=E2=80=99m also aware that it=
=E2=80=99s going to take more than technological innovation to get there. S=
o we explore all of the nitty-gritty, from policy to economics to culture t=
o, of course, entrepreneurship, that=E2=80=99s required for a technology to=
 have a real positive impact on billions of lives. I hope we come out the o=
ther side with a more deeply-earned optimism.=20
For our first season, we=E2=80=99re starting at the foundation: energy, spe=
cifically nuclear and fusion energy.=20
We=E2=80=99re unabashedly techno-optimists. More energy means more growth, =
and growth is good. But we=E2=80=99re realists, too. More energy is great. =
How do we get there?=20
It=E2=80=99s easy to say, =E2=80=9CBUILD MORE NUCLEAR.=E2=80=9D Being pro-n=
uclear is an obvious position to hold in tech at this point. But we=E2=80=
=99ve had nuclear reactors for seven decades, and its growth has stagnated =
in the West. Figuring out how to build more nuclear, how to make it cheap e=
nough that the market demands it, is the tricky part. That=E2=80=99s exactl=
y what we=E2=80=99ll cover.
We=E2=80=99ll also hear from people who are working to create energy abunda=
nce through other sources, like solar, wind, synthetic fuels, and even foss=
il fuels.=C2=A0
And then, in the second half of the season, we=E2=80=99ll turn our attentio=
n to the future energy source people are most excited by: fusion [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/d2352003-4bdc-4d6c-91d0-47d61daeaf87?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
I=E2=80=99m not an expert in these topics. I=E2=80=99m here to learn as we =
go. But having someone who knows where to look and who to talk to and how t=
o contextualize everything is key. So each season, I=E2=80=99m teaming up w=
ith a co-host who actually knows what they=E2=80=99re talking about in the =
space, and for Season 1, I=E2=80=99m thrilled to co-host with  [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/ce83c3e7-8f35-4c58-bf3d-8188c6f6676a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Julia DeWahl [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/ce83c3e7-8f35-4c58-bf3d-8188c6f6676a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Julia was an early employee at Opendoor, worked on Starlink at SpaceX, and =
is now on the founding team at a nuclear startup, Antares. Her piece, Nucle=
ar energy: past, present, and future [ https://substack.com/redirect/49030d=
76-fbdc-46eb-a22b-92498445e894?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is the resource I leaned on most heavily when I w=
as getting up to speed on nuclear.
We=E2=80=99re launching the first two episodes on October 27th. Getting ear=
ly momentum helps a ton =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99d love to get featured by Appl=
e and Spotify so we can reach a wider audience =E2=80=94 so I would really =
appreciate it if you subscribed wherever you listen to podcasts. We=E2=80=
=99ve put a ton of work into this and I hope you enjoy and learn as much as=
 I have!=C2=A0
Of course, I=E2=80=99ll still be in your inbox every Tuesday and Friday, an=
d I hope that the podcast makes my writing better by helping me understand =
the nuance behind the breakthroughs.=C2=A0
(2) Terraform Industries Produces Methane from CO2 and Sunlight [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/0f7f2edf-137c-41bc-b5b4-6745d46019ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Age of Miracles=E2=80=99 first season focuses on nuclear fission and fusion=
 power because they represent the biggest delta between potential and reali=
ty in energy. But really, we just want much, much more energy =E2=80=94 sol=
ar, wind, geothermal, synthetic fuels, gas. Energy is prosperity.=20
One of the guests we had on the podcast to discuss other energy sources =E2=
=80=94 specifically solar and synthetic fuels =E2=80=94 was Casey Handmer, =
the founder and CEO of Terraform Industries. Terraform=E2=80=99s plan [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/f1cbdbfb-32fb-42af-8a9c-f9477a733c80?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is to make cheap =
hydrocarbons from CO2 direct air capture and sunlight. In other words, use =
solar energy to pull carbon from the sky, run it through an electrolyzer, a=
nd spit out carbon neutral gas on the other side.=20
Yesterday, for the first time, they did it.=20
Terraform has been one of my favorite companies for a while =E2=80=94 I=E2=
=80=99ve mentioned it a few times in Not Boring =E2=80=94 because it uses s=
olar, which is basically just good for electricity generation, to make fuel=
s that can be used to power a bunch of the things that use fuel today, like=
 planes and ships. They=E2=80=99re starting with methane, but with a little=
 extra ingenuity, can make any hydrocarbon, including oil. Great step in th=
at direction.=20
And in his free time, Casey also netted a prize for helping discover the fi=
rst word as part of the Vesuvius Challenge=E2=80=A6=20
(3) First word discovered in unopened Herculaneum scroll by 21yo computer s=
cience student [ https://substack.com/redirect/5170a1d9-0301-4ada-b888-c3d4=
fa6b8c0b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
From Scroll Prize
That is until Luke Farritor, a contestant of the Vesuvius Challenge [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/e3ca4a70-0b1c-4111-a527-570d29dcd2bd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], became the first p=
erson in two millennia to see an entire word from within an unopened scroll=
 this August. For that, we are thrilled to award Luke a $40,000 First Lette=
rs Prize, which required contestants to find at least 10 letters in a 4 cm2=
 area in a scroll.
We covered the Vesuvius Challenge launch in March 2023 in the Weekly Dose, =
and just 7 months later the Nat Friedman-backed competition is awarding its=
 first prize for the discovery of =E2=80=9Cthe first word.=E2=80=9D [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/fb5ff401-9294-402c-923d-791806427dae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Let=E2=80=99s take =
a step back, here=E2=80=99s what we wrote about the challenge at the time:
About 300 years ago, we discovered ancient scrolls (Herculaneum Papyri) fro=
m the library of Julius Ceasar=E2=80=99s father-in-law=E2=80=99s villa (79 =
AD). The scrolls were carbonized by volcanic heat, but preserved. They=E2=
=80=99re currently too delicate to unroll, but if we were able to read them=
 it would double the corpus of literature we have from antiquity.
A team of researchers recently developed a method called =E2=80=9Cvirtual u=
nwrapping=E2=80=9D that digitally unrolls and reads the scroll without phys=
ically opening it.
Now, a team led by Nat Friedman and Daniel Gross open sourcing the challeng=
e [ https://substack.com/redirect/e3ca4a70-0b1c-4111-a527-570d29dcd2bd?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to read th=
e Herculaneum Papyri. After 275 years, the ancient puzzle of the Herculaneu=
m Papyri has been reduced to a software problem.
Well, it looks like that software problem is starting to get solved. Luke F=
arritor, a 21-year old computer scientist built on work from Casey Handmer =
to identify the first word in the Herculaneum scrolls. The first word is=E2=
=80=A6drumroll please=E2=80=A6
"=CF=80=CE=BF=CF=81=CF=86=CF=85=CF=81=CE=B1=CF=82" which means "purple dye"=
 or "cloths of purple." OK OK, a bit anticlimactic. No secrets of the ancie=
nt world revealed (other than maybe a proclivity for purple clothing) yet. =
But we=E2=80=99re early, and now we=E2=80=99re making real progress. Our be=
t is that this thing will be fully decoded in the next year.
(4) Ultra-fast deep-learned CNS tumour classification during surgery [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/9d523e09-1107-4c88-8109-c3ac0ac7d968?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
C. Vermeulen [ https://substack.com/redirect/425f2406-7b1b-4820-a865-355681=
1c5c99?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
, M. Pag=C3=A8s-Gallego [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f396dd1-2bb3-4180-=
927b-7aa68bb1ccd0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] for Nature
We conclude that machine-learned diagnosis based on low-cost intraoperative=
 sequencing can assist neurosurgical decision-making, potentially preventin=
g neurological comorbidity and avoiding additional surgeries.
Central nervous system (CNS) tumors are among the most lethal cancers, espe=
cially in children, and their treatment requires a balance between thorough=
 removal and preserving neurological function. It=E2=80=99s a tight rope. A=
ccurate pre-surgical diagnosis is crucial to inform surgical strategy, but =
current methods based on pre-operative imaging and intra-operative analysis=
 can sometimes be inconclusive. Essentially, surgeons have a plan until the=
y get punched in the face with new information mid-surgery.
These researchers developed "Sturgeon," an AI that rapidly classifies CNS t=
umors during surgery. Within 90 minutes, Sturgeon accurately diagnosed 45 o=
ut of 50 samples in retrospective tests and demonstrated its real-time appl=
icability in 25 surgeries, suggesting potential for better-informed intraop=
erative decisions.
AI as a co-pilot seems to be the first big use-case of the AI revolution. H=
elp lawyers redline contracts. Help engineers write code and debug. And, wi=
th Sturgeon, help doctors perform more accurate real-time diagnoses during =
surgery.
(5) Charles Feeney, philanthropist who gave away his billions, dies at 92 [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/c9532547-e624-4cf4-99ba-8e8701c3cadc?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brian Murphy for The Washington Post
He decided to give nearly all of it away =E2=80=94 close to $8 billion =E2=
=80=94 donation by donation, charity by charity, year after year.
You=E2=80=99ve probably never heard of Charles Feeney. And that is by desig=
n. The pioneer of duty-free shops and a tech investor, Feeney gave away his=
 $8 billion fortune over the last decades of his life, and he did so quietl=
y, taking pains to conceal the identity behind his donations. Warren Buffet=
t once presented an award to Feeney calling him =E2=80=9Cmy hero and Bill G=
ates=E2=80=99s hero =E2=80=94 he should be everybody=E2=80=99s hero.=E2=80=
=9D
There=E2=80=99s nothing wrong with seeking notoriety in philanthropy. It=E2=
=80=99s certainly true that people give, in part, to make themselves feel g=
ood. And hey, if that=E2=80=99s the case, then we should lean into that and=
 make people feel good when they give. But there is something special about=
 Feeney=E2=80=99s approach to philanthropy. Amass a fortune, give it all aw=
ay during your lifetime, live a modest life, and do it all in relative secr=
et. The world would certainly be a better, more optimistic place if we had =
more Charles Feeneys.=20
Bonus: Congrats to Loom on its $975 million sale to Atlassian =F0=9F=A5=B3=
=20
Packy here. Yesterday, Atlassian announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
35b51e21-e8aa-4d6d-902e-8bcc196dfbdc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that it=E2=80=99s acquiring async video comp=
any Loom for $975 million, in cash, in this economy.=20
Normally, we don=E2=80=99t cover M&A activity in the Weekly Dose, and Loom =
isn=E2=80=99t a portfolio company. So why are we including this one?=20
Because this was TechCrunch=E2=80=99s coverage of the deal:
When I wrote Optimism [ https://www.notboring.co/p/optimism ] last summer, =
one of the motivating factors was just how negative the media coverage of t=
ech is. It=E2=80=99s why we started the Weekly Dose, as a little counterbal=
ance. This TC article is a good example of the snarky attitude towards tech=
 that=E2=80=99s all too common. The sarcasm oozes off the page.=20
So let me just say: if Not Boring ever sells for $975 million in cash, clea=
nly clearing the pref stack and making me and many of my employees generati=
onally wealthy, I too will put a positive spin on the acquisition. Big cong=
rats to the Loom team on a great outcome after nearly a decade=E2=80=99s wo=
rth of hard work.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

